A Compendium of Programming Language Mascots
===============================================================================

HERO IMAGE OF ALL THE MASCOTS AT A LAN PARTY

%% Programming language mascots have become an integral part of many programming language communities, serving as symbols of identity, culture, and fun. From the early days of computing to the present, mascots have evolved from simple symbols to fully developed characters with personalities and backstories. In this article, we will explore the history of programming language mascots, their significance in the programming community, and look at some of the most iconic mascots that have emerged over the years. We also introduce Mech's new mascot, Mika the mech, a friendly and little character designed to represent the Mech programming language and its community.

***

Although I've looked around, I can't find any comprehensive articles on the history and state of the art of programming language mascots. So this is the article I was hoping to find -- we cover the past, present, and future of programming language mascots, exploring their origins, cultures, and impacts on the programming community as a whole.

Having now looked into the history, *right now* is actually the exact right time to start looking backwards at mascot over the years; as you'll see, the history of mascots in programming languages is still very recent (beginning in just 1967) and rapidly evolving. With AI lowering barriers to language development, we are likely to see an explosion of new programming languages and associated mascots in the coming years, making it a good time to take stock of where we are and how we got here.

So in this article we'll look at the most iconic mascots in programming language history, their design inspirations, the artists behind them, and the impact they've had on the programming community. We'll also look at some newer mascots, trends in mascot design, and where mascots might go in the future.

Information about mascots in programming languages can be hard to find; this article collects knowledge that may only be contained in scattered blogs, forum discussions, and social media threads -- certainly not academic journals. By compiling it all in one place, I hope the article can serve as a comprehensive resource for anyone interested in the fascinating world of programming language mascots. Also, if anyone finds mistakes, has facts to add, or citations to include, let me know by making a [pull request](https://github.com/mech-web/website). Also this article should be a living compendium, so as new mascots emerge, please create a pull request to add them to the compendium.

The paper is organized as follows. We first present a brief history of mascots in popular culture and in the field of computing generally in §1. In §2, we look at the earliest instances of programming language mascots, which were mostly "quasi-mascots" that served as symbols or logos for their languages. Then in §3, we look at the emergence of fully developed characters with names, personalities, and backstories. Indie and recent mascots are covered in in §4. Finally, in §5, we present a comprehensive catalog of programming language mascots which we hope will be expanded over time as new mascots emerge.

1. History of Mascots
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

> mascot - an object, an animal or a lucky person, who wards off bad luck by their mere presence [GRAPHEINE].

(1.1) In Popular Culture

The word "mascot" comes from the Provençal word "mascoto", which was adopted into French as "mascotte" in the late 19th century. The term originally referred to a talisman or charm that was believed to bring good luck, and it was often associated with animals, objects, or people that were thought to have protective or auspicious qualities. For example, albatrosses were considered good luck for sailors [^ALBATROSS], and rabbits' feet and are still widely believed to bring good fortune. The idea of a mascot transcends specific cultures and has been present in various forms throughout history, from ancient civilizations to modern times.

By the 19th century, mascots had found their way into sports and business culture. In sports, the first mascot was a bat boy named Chic who the team said brought them good luck. The first living animal mascot was Handsom Dan, a bulldog who became the official mascot of Yale University in 1889. Since then the idea has since evolved into the modern vision of a mascot with characters like the Philly Phanatic, who has his own following as big as the team itself. In business, the first mascot could be considered the Quaker Oats Man, who was introduced in 1877 to help sell oatmeal. Today, most companies have adopted some kind of mascot to represent their brand and connect with customers, to the point where entire brands are built around just mascots alone, such as the Geico Gecko[^GENERAL].

https://www.theculturecrush.com/feature/mascots

https://grapheine.com/en/magazine/a-history-of-mascots/

https://news.yale.edu/2019/07/03/handsome-dan-130-year-old-legacy

(1.2) In Computing

By the time computers came around in the mid 20th century, the idea of a mascot was already well-established in popular and corporate culture, with mascots including Mickey Mouse, the Michelin Man, and the Pillsbury Doughboy appearing in all forms of media. It was only a matter of time before mascots found their way into the world of computing.

Computing has always been a field where fun, creativity, and silliness are paramount. However, early computing products were designed and marketed as military hardware or custom-built research equiment, industries which didn't lend to the fun, silly, and creative branding and marketing that is common in consumer products. But that of course never stopped people and subcultures within computing from having fun and expressing themselves creatively, even sometimes in ridiculous ways. As the computing industry grew and diversified -- and of course commercialized -- the need for branding and user engagement led to the widespread adoption of marketing tools like mascots.

![Wile E. Coyote operate the UNIVAC "electronic brain", which feeds him ideas on how to capture Bugs Bunny. The twist of the episode is that Bugs Bunny is hiding inside the UNIVAC the entire time, sabotaging the coyote's plans.](/images/univac.png)

The first even tangential appearance of a mascot used with a computer was in 1956, when Warner Brothers released the Looney Tunes cartoon ["To Hare is Human"](https://www.supercartoons.net/cartoon/to-hare-is-human/) directed by Chuck Jones[HARE]. In the cartoon, Wile E. Coyote uses a [UNIVAC computer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNIVAC) to generate ideas on how to catch Bugs Bunny, who is later revealed to be intercepting the UNIVAC output to sabotage Wile E. Coyote[^GENAI].

I can't find any character or mascot associated in any way with a computing product before this instance, probably because computers before 1956 did not exist outside of research labs and military installations. I leave open the possibility there is some internal mascot I cannot find on the general Internet, but this cartoon would seem to be the first public depiction of a branded computer system with any kind of personality or character.

It wasn't until 1976 that the idea of using a mascot to represent a computing product was adopted by industry, when BSD Unix adopted Beastie the BSD Daemon as a mascot. Beastie was created by Phil Foglio, Mike O'Brien, and John Lasseter [BEASTIE], who intended Beastie's demonic form to evoke the idea of a background process in Unix systems, which are often referred to as "daemons". This started the tradition of using the mascot to represent and personify features of the computing system -- although as we'll see the origin stories and meanings behind them can have varying levels of depth and sincerity.

Since the introduction of Beastie, the open source community has frequently used mascots to represent various projects and movements including the GNU Project's GNU (a wildebeest), Linux's [Tux the penguin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tux_(mascot)), Glenda the Plan 9 bunny, the Android robot, and many others [^OSTAN]. Mascots have also become an important part of commerical software products, such as Microsoft's Clippy. More recently large tech companies have even introdiced AI assistants like Cortant, Siri, and Alexa, which serve the role of mascots for their respective platforms [^CORTANA].

2. Proto Mascots
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

REDDit USER ASKS WHY DO PROGRAMMING LANGUAGES HAVE MASCOTS?

Good question! After all, programming languages are simply tools -- does your hammer need a mascot? No! Then why should a programming langauge?

But really, programming languages are more than just tools -- they are also communities, cultures, and ecosystems. Today, researchers are talking about how programming languages are social and cultural phenomena that shape and are shaped by the communities that use them, not just tools or mathematical systems, which is the dominant perspective [AJK16]. In this context, mascots can be seen as a way to represent and personify the culture of a programming language community, making it more relatable and engaging for its users.

Some other reasons why mascots are used in programming languages include:

- **Branding and Marketing:** Mascots help create a memorable image for a programming language, making it easier for developers to recognize and remember it among many options. Along with a logo, brand colors, and a good name [^GOODNAME], a mascot can be an important part of a modern programming language's identity and marketing strategy.
- **Community Building:** Many mascots are licensed to be used by the community, so they can be used legitimately in user groups, conferences, and other community events. Other mascots are community designed and driven, which further strengthens the bond between the language and its users.
- **Engagement:** Mascots add an element of personality to a programming language, making it more approachable and engaging for users. It's common for the mascot to be an avatar which guides new users through tutorials and documentation.
- **Fundraising:** No one wants to pay money for a compiler, even people who like and use it. Plenty of people are willing to pay money for a plushie or t-shirt with a cute character on it.
- **Fun:** Sometimes there doesn't have to be a purpose to a thing except to have fun with it. 

But what is a mascot exactly? I'd like to introduce a brief taxonomy for mascots, because there are really two distinct types of mascots that we'll see throughout programming language history, and it's useful to draw a distinction between them for the purposes of this catalog.

The first category is the **"proper-mascot"**, which is what we all think of when we imagine a mascot: a distinct character with a name, a personality, it usually has a backstory, and is used consistently and officially by the language's community or creators. Examples include Java's Duke, Rust's Ferris, and Go's Gopher.

The second variety we will call **"quasi-mascots"**, which are more like symbols or logos that have taken on a mascot-like role in the community, but lack the full characteristics of a proper mascot -- they may not have a name, personality, or backstory, and their use may be more informal or unofficial. Examples include Python's python, Perl's camel, and Swift's swift. These are icons of the langauge, but they they lack that certain personality and consistency that makes them true mascots.

What we see in the history of programming langauges is that the earliest mascots were quasi-mascots, and over time as the culture of programming languages evolved, proper mascots began to emerge as these quasi-mascots became more developed and popular ways to represent programming langauge communities.

So let's take a look at the history of programming language mascots and some of the most iconic ones out there!

***

Mascots were not always a feature in programming languages. In the early days of computing, programming languages were primarily designed for professional use by scientists, engineers, and mathematicians, and they lacked the playful and approachable elements that mascots would later bring to languages.

The earliest programming language names were acronyms or abbreviations that described their purpose or functionality, such as Fortran (Formula Translation, 1957), COBOL (Common Business-Oriented Language, 1960), and LISP (LISt Processing, 1960). These names were often chosen for their technical accuracy rather than their marketability or appeal to a broader audience. Even the first langauge Plankalkül, created by Konrad Zuse in the 1940s, simply described what it was -- a plan calculus. 

It wasn't until the ISWIM language by Landin in 1966 that we see the first programming language name that evokes a philosophy or feeling rather than just technical functionality [ISWIM]. ISWIM stands for If You See What I Mean, reflecting the idea that programming should be about expressing ideas in a way that is easy to understand and reason about.

But it is the Logo langauge from 1967 designed by Feurzeig, Papert, and Solomon that can be reasonably construed as having the first instance of a programming langauge mascot: the Logo turtle. 

(1.1) Logo's Turtle (1967)

The first programming language mascot is arguably the Logo turtle, which was introduced in 1967 as part of the Logo programming language developed by Wally Feurzeig, Seymour Papert, and Cynthia Solomon. What makes the turtle particularly significant in the history of programming language mascots is that it wasn't just a marketing afterthought or a cute symbol slapped onto an existing language -- the turtle was integral to Logo's entire design philosophy and pedagogical approach.

The inspiration for the turtle came from the work of neurophysiologist William Grey Walter, who in the late 1940s built a series of autonomous robots called "tortoises" that could navigate their environment and respond to light. These early robots, named Elmer and Elsie, were designed to demonstrate that complex behavior could emerge from simple rules -- a concept that deeply influenced Papert's thinking about how children could learn about mathematics and computation.

When Logo was developed at BBN (Bolt, Beranek and Newman) in Cambridge, Massachusetts, the turtle started as a physical robot -- a small wheeled device with a pen that could be raised or lowered. Children could program this robot to move forward, backward, and turn at various angles, leaving behind a trail of ink as it traced geometric patterns across large sheets of paper spread on the floor. The dome-shaped shell that covered the robot's electronics gave it its turtle-like appearance, and the name stuck.

What made the turtle revolutionary was Papert's concept of "body syntonic reasoning" -- the idea that children could learn abstract mathematical concepts by putting themselves in the turtle's position and thinking about how they themselves would move to create a particular shape. Instead of thinking about coordinate geometry in the abstract Cartesian way that adults had learned for centuries, a child could think "if I want to draw a square, I walk forward, turn 90 degrees, walk forward, turn 90 degrees..." This made programming accessible to children as young as four or five years old, something that was unthinkable for Logo's contemporaries.

As computers became more capable of handling graphics in the 1970s, the physical turtle robot evolved into Turtle Graphics -- a graphical representation on a computer screen that could draw lines as it moved. This is what most people think of when they remember Logo from their childhood computer labs.

The turtle doesn't have a proper name in the same way that later mascots like Duke or Ferris do[^2], and it doesn't have an elaborate backstory or personality. In this sense, it fits more into our category of quasi-mascots rather than proper mascots. But what it lacks in character development, it more than makes up for in pedagogical significance and cultural impact. The turtle became so synonymous with Logo that the very concept of "turtle graphics" is now used generically to describe any programming environment where you control a cursor that draws as it moves.

ROS TURTLE BOT AND TURTLE TUTORIAL GRAPHIC HERE

The legacy of the Logo turtle extends far beyond the Logo language itself. The idea of learning to program by controlling a simple avatar influenced countless educational programming environments that followed, from [Karel the Robot](https://compedu.stanford.edu/karel-reader/docs/python/en/chapter1.html) to modern tools like Scratch. Even today, Python's built-in [turtle](https://docs.python.org/3/library/turtle.html) module pays homage to Logo's groundbreaking approach to making programming accessible and visual.

Even the physical The physical turtle robots themselves have had surprising longevity. The Open Robotics Initiative has released multiple generations of TurtleBot robots for education and research, carrying forward the spirit of those original dome-shelled robots from the 1960s. In a field where technologies become obsolete within years, the turtle has remained relevant for over half a century -- a testament to the power of good design and pedagogical insight.

https://www.alancsmith.co.uk/logo/

(1.2) CAML / OCaml / Perl's Camels (1985 / 1987 / 2005)

Given there are many kinds of animals but relatively few programming langauges (especially in the 80s), it's odd then that two completely different langauges would end up with the same animal as their mascot. As far as I can tell, it's mostly an accident of history.

(1.2.1) CAML / OCaml's Camels

CAML (Categorical Abstract Machine Language), developed in the 1985 at INRIA in France, was designed as a practical implementation of the ML (Meta Language) family of languages, combining ML's functional programming approach with the categorical abstract machine (CAM) as its computational model. The name CAML was thus an acronym combining "CAM" and "ML". This represents the first instance in a long history of a programming language being named after an animal. The authors played into this in one of their original logos, which featured a two-hump (Bactrian) camel.

Since then, CAML's descendant OCaml, developed in 1996, has continued to use the Bactrian camel as its mascot, although today it's evolved into a more stylized and modern design. Despite CAML/OCaml's association with camels, this mascot is still really a quasi mascot for those languages as you don't find it anyhwere except the logo -- it doesn't have a name or personality, but you still see camels used in shirts and merchandise, and the OCaml community has embraced the camel as a symbol of the language using camel and desert imagery in names of packages and tooling *e.g.* the [Dune package manager](https://github.com/ocaml/dune).

(1.2.2) Perl's Camel

Designed by Larry Wall, Perl was released a few years after CAML in 1987. In fact, Perl got its name because while Wall wanted to name the language Pearl, it already existed at the time as the PEARL (Process and experiment automation realtime language) language[^PERL]. It strikes me as odd then that a camel or onion would be associated with Perl instead of a clam, which would make sense given the name. Or even an actual pearl. Here's the story of how it happened.

The camel's entry into programming language iconography began in 1991 with the publication of O'Reilly's "Programming Perl" by Larry Wall, the creator of Perl [^BENTLEY]. O'Reilly Media had a distinctive house style at the time: all their technical books featured 19th-century engravings of animals on their covers due to their lapsed copyright protections. These weren't chosen for any deep symbolic meaning -- the O'Reilly staff would just go through Dover Publications' pictorial archives and pick whatever animal images were available and hadn't been used yet. For "Programming Perl," they chose a dromedary (one hump) camel. It's not clear exactly *why* a camel in particular was chosen, or who actually chose it -- whether it was Larry Wall himself or an O'Reilly editor [^PROGRAMMINGPERL].

Either way, as Programming Perl was many users' first introduction to the language, the camel quickly became associated with Perl in the minds of many developers. But unfortunately, the genesis of the camel imagery having gone through a publisher meant that O'Reilly Media owned the copyright to that camel image, not the Perl community.

Despite their ownership, O'Reilly has been generous about granting permission for the community to use it at conferences, on merchandise, and in other Perl-related contexts. But it remains O'Reilly's intellectual property, and they do still maintain a restrictions that no other programming books about Perl can use a camel on the cover. 

(1.2.3) Camel vs. Camel

This has led to an odd situation where Perl's most recognizable symbol isn't actually controlled by the language's community or foundation. In fact, the the Perl Foundation, recognizing this limitation, adopted an onion as their official logo. But decades of association mean that when most people think of Perl, they still picture that O'Reilly camel, not an onion.

So now there are two programming languages associated with camel imagery. How do they handle this without causing confusion? The first answer is that they don't, it's very confusing. But to the extent that they try, there is an informal convention in some circles: one hump camels for Perl, two hump camels for OCaml. It's a neat distinction, but it doesn't solve the fundamental problem that both languages were using the same animal.

Either way, neither the Perl camel nor the OCaml camel is really a proper mascot in our taxonomy -- neither has a name, a personality, or a backstory beyond "we needed a book cover" and "it's literally just our name." And we will see the same in other languages named after anmials -- like Python and Swift -- where they don't have an actual mascot character, but rather just the animal itself as a symbol of the language.

