(3.2) Scratch's ScratchCat (2004)

Scratch is a programming language for education and creativity developed by the Lifelong Kindergarten Group at MIT, and it has become one of the most popular programming languages for children and beginners. Scratch's mascot, ScratchCat, is a cute and friendly cat character that serves as the face of the Scratch community and brand. Being an educational language, it has roots that trace back to the Logo language and its turtle mascot, so it makes sense that Scratch would also have an engaging mascot for its young users.

Before they (ScratchCat's gender is unknown but they are described using they/them pronouns by one of the creators of Scratch, so we will describe them thusly) were a mascot tey can first be seen as a default sprite in the Scratch editor as a top down view of a cat loaf. But the first actualy depiction of ScratchCat as a character was in the beta version circa 2004, depicted here.

ScratchCat is often depicted in various poses and scenarios, showcasing their playful and creative nature. The character is designed to be approachable and friendly, making it appealing to children and beginners who are just starting to learn programming.

But Scratch extends this idea beyond individual cognition into networked creativity. ScratchCat is therefore not merely a successor to the turtle as a programmable cursor, but the central figure through which programs are created, exchanged, and remixed across a global community.

Becasue the thing about scratch is that it's not just a programming language, but an editor, and a whole community for sharing programs. Scratchat is therefore used in ways that other languages can't, where he's a literal avatar in the editor, meaning that h'es probably been remixed and used more than any other programming language mascot in history. ScratchCat is the most widely used programming language mascot of all time, with millions of users creating and sharing projects featuring ScratchCat on the Scratch website. Despite Duke's massive marketing budget and ubiquitous nature, you can still find Java users all over who have no idea Java even has a mascot. Thats because you can use JAva without ever seeing Duke onece. But Scratch cat is omnipresent, they're all over scratch, there's no way to avoid them, and so their mindshare is much higher amongst scratch users than Duke's is among Java users.

