Lisp and Javascript both have unofficial alien mascots that have been used in various contexts, but neither has an official mascot that is widely recognized by the community. Instead, they seem to be more of a meme or inside joke within their respective communities rather than a formal mascot.

(5.6) Mojo's Flame (2023)

Mojo is a new programming language that was announced in 2023 by Modular, a company founded by Chris Lattner, the creator of Swift. Mojo is designed to be a high-performance language for AI and machine learning applications. Mojo's branding dictates that the name is actually Mojo🔥, with the flame included. They even support a `.🔥` file extension. 

Modular has used an anthropomorphized flame as the mascot for Mojo, which is often depicted in a cute and friendly style. The flame doesn't appear to have a name, although it has been called "Mojo the Fireball" in a comic book released by Modular. The comic book also features the characters Ava the engineer and Max in the "inference optimizer", which is a nod to their MAX framework. Max is also featured in various marketing and community contexts, including their blog. However, I cannot find Ava outside of the comic book, so she doesn't appear to be a mascot for Modular, but rather just a character for the comic.

https://www.modular.com/mojo

https://comic.modular.com

https://www.modular.com/blog/modular-2025-year-in-review

