(5.12) .Net Bot

The .Net Bet is a mascot for the entire .Net ecosystem[^6], which includes multiple programming languages such as C#, F#, and VB.Net. The .Net Bot was created by Microsoft as a way to represent the .Net platform and its various components, including the programming languages that run on it. The bot is often depicted as a friendly and approachable character, designed to make the .Net ecosystem more accessible and engaging for developers. While the .Net Bot is not specific to any one programming language, it serves as a unifying mascot for the entire .Net community. 

https://github.com/dotnet-bot
https://mod-dotnet-bot.net/create-your-bot/
https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/shows/one-dev-minute/what-is-the-dotnet-bot--one-dev-question
https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/commits?author=dotnet-bot&since=2014-11-07&until=2014-11-08

(5.13) C++'s Keith the Diseased Rat

There's an urban legends that C++'s mascot is a diseased rat named Keith who blew his leg off with a shotgun, referring to the tendancy for C++ users to "shoot themselves in the foot" due to the language's complexity and potential for errors. 
Part of the rumor is that it was created by GNU founder Richard Stallman as a way to criticize C++ for its complexity and potential for misuse.
However, this is not true; Keith is not an official mascot, but more of a physical manifestation of C++'s spirit on in our material realm.
https://lunduke.locals.com/post/5111104/no-the-c-mascot-is-not-a-diseased-rat-named-keith

